  "doc_id": "36931",
  "text": "It has been also suggested that unprocessed corn can be efficiently fed to beef cattle since the pericarp of the kernel is almost entirely cracked by chewing both during eating and during rumination [CITATION_1] . Since minimizing the surface area available to microbial attack decreases the rate of starch digestion, thereby maintaining ruminal pH at an optimal level [CITATION_2] , minimal processing of corn grain by slightly cracking the pericarp may slow the rate of starch digestion. Even though results in the present study did not show the superior nutrient digestibility of whole corn against those of flaked corn, we showed similar digestibilities with similar amounts of corn particles in the feces between the two treatments. Therefore, our results suggest that unprocessed corns may be more effectively utilized for the beef cattle, if one considers the cost in processing corn.",
